Sep 24, 2019, 12:21 PM
Ben Fickes
Okay one thing that came to my mind from the sermon that also relates to my dad: pastor Adam said “a lot of the time, in Christian circles, we make our children our idols. We make them the center of our lives. But <something about it being not good> and they will one day hate you for it.” And I thought about my dad - I do think Josh and I were close to the center of his universe. And I’m not saying that’s good, and I certainly think children can be an idol, as he said. But I don’t think I could ever hate my dad, even in knowing ways that his attention wasn’t necessarily good. And I can’t quite put words to it but when I heard him say things like that, it just put this picture of parents and children that revolves around angst and keeping track of wrongs. And I have felt that truthfully, but I think it really shifted after my dad died because I realized how dumb some things that bothered me were and how dumb it was that I couldn’t talk to him about other things. And I think people do keep track of how their well-meaning parents wrong them so I’m not saying it’s not legit but I think it’s an incredible luxury to be able to fault pick your parents who care because a lot of people don’t have parents or parents who care. I still feel like I can’t express what I’m trying to but overall it just made me feel like the particular line about hate was almost threatening parents and also dismissed the complexity between parents and children

Ben Fickes
Anyways in the dream I was at home with my family and my dad came in and told us that he was poisoned and dying. I asked him who poisoned him and he said it was his own body. He said that everything ached, he was in a lot of pain, and he was dying soon. It made me really upset in the dream and I told him we wouldn’t be able to make it without him. Then I woke up. And ever since I was little my dad always told me that after I woke up from a nightmare, I can always remind myself that it was only a dream. And that’s what I still do. Aug 27, 2019, 10:16 PM
Ben Fickes
So the story is that we sang a song called “There is another in the fire.” And (part of) the refrain is something like:
“I hear heaven roar
As the space between wears thin
I feel the ground begin to shake
As the prison walls cave in
There is another in the fire
Standing here with me”
And I thought about my dad singing that. Because the walls literally caved in on him, and he died in the fire. But I imagined him singing it as he was dying. And I hope he felt Gods presence in it. And he mention of this world as a prison made me think that, no matter how much I wish he were here, he’s in a better place
